const e={title:"Trading Journal",tagline:"A record of every trade — and a set of rules to stop the worst ones.",what:"The Trading Journal is where you open, track, and book stock, options, and intraday trades, with automatic profit/loss calculation and optional rules that enforce trading discipline before a bad trade ever gets placed. It isn't just a record of trades after the fact — it's built to sit between you and your worst impulses in the moment you're about to act on them.",howTo:[{heading:"Open a trade",body:'Choose a Kind — Swing, FnO, or Intraday (FnO and Intraday also allow Short direction; Swing is always Long) — then enter the instrument name, purchase date, entry price, stop-loss price, target price, quantity, and an optional note. A live P/L preview updates as you type: "If target hit" is |target − entry| × qty, "If SL hit" is −|SL − entry| × qty, so you see your real risk:reward before you commit.'},{heading:"Know the validation rules",body:"Instrument is required; entry, stop-loss, target, and quantity must all be greater than zero. For a Long trade, stop loss must sit below entry and target above it; for a Short trade, it's the reverse. If Settings → Trading has discipline rules turned on — minimum risk:reward ratio, maximum risk % of capital, or a per-kind diversification cap (max position value = capital ÷ N, max N open trades of that kind) — a trade that breaks one of them won't go through."},{heading:"Book a trade when you exit it",body:"Tap Profit or Loss on an open trade to open a confirmation modal showing the realized P/L (the formula differs for long vs. short) and the outcome date. Intraday trades must be booked the same day they were opened — square off same day, no exceptions — while Swing and FnO booking dates are editable. Any booked trade can be reopened later if you booked it by mistake."},{heading:"Track your stats",body:"Starting capital, Net P/L (booked only), Current balance (capital + net P/L, shown green or red against your starting figure), and booked-vs-open trade counts give you the account-level view alongside the trade-level one."},{heading:"Use the Calendar view",body:"Navigate month by month. Each day gets a color dot — green or red by that day's net booked P/L, gray if only a learning note exists with no trades. Selecting a day shows its booked trades plus a Positive/Negative/No trades badge, and a free-text daily learning box lets you record what worked or what didn't, independent of whether you traded that day at all."}],why:`Trading accounts don't usually blow up because of one bad analysis — they blow up because of a handful of well-documented emotional impulses acting faster than judgment can catch them. The Journal is built specifically against those impulses:

• The discipline rules exist to fight revenge trading and over-concentration before they happen, not to critique them afterward. A minimum risk:reward ratio stops you from taking a trade where the math was never in your favor, even if you're certain "this one's different." A max-risk-% cap stops a losing streak from escalating into a bet-it-all trade made out of frustration. A diversification cap stops you from pouring capital into one conviction position after a string of wins makes you feel invincible. Each rule targets a specific, named failure mode — not trading in general.

• Booking as a two-step flow — preview, then confirm — is a deliberate speed bump. Exiting a trade is often an emotional moment: panic on a loss, euphoria on a gain, both of which push toward hasty action. Forcing a confirmation modal that shows the actual realized number before it's final adds one beat of friction exactly when a beat of friction is most valuable — enough to notice if you're closing a winner too early out of fear, or holding a loser too long out of hope.

• The live P/L preview at entry — not just at exit — makes risk visible when it's still avoidable. Seeing "if SL hit: −₹4,200" before you place the trade, not after, is the only time that number can actually change your behavior. By the time a trade is open, the risk is already taken.

• Intraday's same-day booking rule enforces the one rule intraday trading cannot survive without. Carrying an intraday position overnight is one of the most common ways a small, defined loss becomes a large, undefined one. Making same-day square-off structurally required — not just advised — removes the "just this once" decision entirely.

• The learning note existing independently of trades matters as much as the trades themselves. A day with no trades still has something to learn — why you sat out, what setup you passed on, whether discipline held. Tying reflection only to executed trades would silently teach you that the days you showed restraint don't count, which is exactly backwards.

Used consistently, the Trading Journal is meant to slow down the exact moments — entry, exit, and the losing streak in between — where speed is the enemy, and to leave behind a record specific enough that next month's trading is informed by this month's mistakes instead of repeating them.`};export{e as default};
